rolled military and would overturn a ban on the military use of space . On 13 May 2008 [LOC Japan] 's powerful lower house of parliament voted to allow [LOC Japan] 's space programs to be utilized for national defense . The legislation is the most recent effort by [LOC Japan] to ascribe more freedom to the tightly controlled military technically known as a self-defense force . The legislation is expected to be approved by the upper house . The legislation is primarily aimed at permitting military use of [LOC Japan] 's civilian-controlled spy satellite network for defense as defined by the pacifist constitution . The bill states that space development has become increasingly important . The bill states that space programs must contribute to ensure peace and safety of international society as well as the national security of [LOC Japan] . The bill does not specify how the programs will be utilized but the satellite network and other assets could potentially be used for surveillance , planning and for a missile defense shield [LOC Japan] is constructing with the [LOC United States] . The bill would overturn a ban on the military use of space imposed on [LOC Japan] 's nascent space program in 1969 . The [MISC U.S.-drafted] 1947 [LOC Constitution] prohibits [LOC Japan] from offensive warfare . The legislation stipulates that all members of the cabinet and not just education , science and technology ministers will be responsible for [LOC Japan] 's future space projects . Inclusion of the defense minister in decisions on space programs introduces the possibility for the military to possess and develop spy satellites . The legislation would establish a special space task force led by the [ORG Prime Minister] and create the new post of space development minister . [LOC Japan] 's [ORG Defense Agency] was upgraded to Ministry status in 2007 . [MISC Japanese] troops were dispatched to a combat zone for the first time since [MISC World War II] in 2004 . The mission in [LOC Iraq]